WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.280 --> 00:00:04.800
All right, we'll go ahead and get started.

2
00:00:05.820 --> 00:00:08.660
Thank you all for joining today, this mini symposium.

3
00:00:08.700 --> 00:00:11.860
This is the Pediatric Cancer From Mechanism to Translation.

4
00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:16.750
The speakers were all selected from abstracts that were

5
00:00:16.780 --> 00:00:17.220
submitted,

6
00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:22.360
reviewed by a panel of folks, and then we put them together, and these are our

7
00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:26.410
speakers today here. And so this session really

8
00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:30.300
highlights how advances in developmental biology, tumor ecosystems,

9
00:00:30.340 --> 00:00:34.280
and molecular precision are reshaping therapeutic strategies

10
00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:37.700
for pediatric cancers. Across solid and hematologic

11
00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:41.320
malignancies, the presenters demonstrate how tumor-specific

12
00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:44.650
transcriptional dependencies, cell state plasticity, and

13
00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:47.940
microenvironmental interactions create actionable

14
00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:48.820
vulnerabilities.

15
00:00:50.500 --> 00:00:54.040
Cutting-edge technologies, including spatial profiling, liquid

16
00:00:54.100 --> 00:00:57.340
biopsy, and engineered cellular immunotherapies are

17
00:00:57.440 --> 00:01:01.300
leveraged to move discoveries rapidly from mechanistic

18
00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:03.460
insight to translational application.

19
00:01:04.740 --> 00:01:08.560
Collectively, these studies emphasize a new paradigm

20
00:01:08.700 --> 00:01:12.540
in pediatric oncology, moving beyond cytotoxic

21
00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:15.460
generalization toward biomarker-driven,

22
00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:19.640
context-aware interventions that aim

23
00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:23.300
to maximize durable responses while minimizing the harm to the developing

24
00:01:23.340 --> 00:01:23.730
child.

25
00:01:24.810 --> 00:01:28.600
The session spans immune surveillance and evasion, transcriptional and

26
00:01:28.640 --> 00:01:32.490
epigenetic rewiring, lineage-specific signaling,

27
00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:36.360
and next-generation immunotherapies, underscoring how precision

28
00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:40.330
medicine in pediatrics must be built on a deep understanding of

29
00:01:40.360 --> 00:01:42.920
the developmental context and tumor evolution.

30
00:01:43.940 --> 00:01:47.540
So each of our speakers will be given 15 minutes in total, 10 minutes

31
00:01:47.640 --> 00:01:50.500
for their presentations and five minutes for their questions.

32
00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:54.140
We ask that if you do have questions, please come to the mic so the people online

33
00:01:54.180 --> 00:01:58.100
will be able to hear you. And we look forward to your engagement

34
00:01:58.160 --> 00:02:01.830
in this session. So our first speaker is Adam Durbin from St.

35
00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:05.600
Jude. His talk is entitled Dysregulated AKT

36
00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:09.250
Signaling Reprograms Osteosarcoma to Drive Selective

37
00:02:09.380 --> 00:02:11.380
Reliance on EP300. Adam?

38
00:02:17.900 --> 00:02:21.700
Thanks, Mark, and thanks to the organizers for giving me the opportunity to

39
00:02:21.860 --> 00:02:22.560
speak here today.

40
00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:25.540
Is this... Yeah. Great. Okay.

41
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.740
I have some disclosures related to compounds and systems that we have developed,

42
00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:33.120
some of which I will be discussing today.

43
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.440
For many years now, it's been increasingly aware within the

44
00:02:38.480 --> 00:02:41.820
community that pediatric cancers really are

45
00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:45.640
diseases where mutations tend to show up in conserved

46
00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:49.620
processes, things like transcriptional regulation, epigenetic regulation of

47
00:02:49.660 --> 00:02:52.660
transcription, and three-dimensional chromatin structure.

48
00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:56.360
And so just underscoring that point, here is some

49
00:02:56.420 --> 00:03:00.200
data from Xiaotu Ma's paper in "Nature" from 2018

50
00:03:00.280 --> 00:03:03.680
demonstrating mutations across multiple different pediatric cancer

51
00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:04.280
lineages.

52
00:03:05.200 --> 00:03:08.940
And you can see exactly that point, that these processes tend to

53
00:03:08.980 --> 00:03:12.900
acquire mutations and become oftentimes dysregulated.

54
00:03:14.060 --> 00:03:17.970
And in collaboration with the Pediatric Dependencies Accelerator, and before that

55
00:03:18.480 --> 00:03:22.060
DepMap, my laboratory has been very focused on thinking about

56
00:03:22.070 --> 00:03:26.060
transcriptional regulation through the lens of epigenetics, and we

57
00:03:26.100 --> 00:03:29.790
have dominantly focused on two targets, these master

58
00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:32.700
histone acetyltransferases, P300 and CBP.

59
00:03:33.820 --> 00:03:37.360
Here in this schematic, you can see the domain structure of P300 and

60
00:03:37.460 --> 00:03:40.920
CBP. These are highly paralogous, oftentimes

61
00:03:41.020 --> 00:03:41.859
co-expressed,

62
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:46.240
lysine acetyltransferases. And these are enzymes.

63
00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:50.120
In the presence of acetyl-CoA, they use this as a cofactor to

64
00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:53.640
acetylate target proteins, including most

65
00:03:53.680 --> 00:03:57.320
famously, histone H3 on lysine 27,

66
00:03:57.380 --> 00:04:00.690
establishing landing spots for bromodomain-containing proteins,

67
00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:02.720
including P300 and CBP,

68
00:04:03.840 --> 00:04:07.580
that form a scaffold to allow for high output target gene expression.

69
00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:11.940
And over the years, we have studied these proteins and

70
00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:15.660
demonstrated that as you look at the DepMap, for

71
00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:19.280
example, you'll find that up to about a quarter of the cell lines in

72
00:04:19.340 --> 00:04:22.770
DepMap are actually uniquely dependent on P300 for survival,

73
00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:27.290
with a smaller fraction being dependent on either CBP or both of these,

74
00:04:28.520 --> 00:04:31.810
suggesting that these are potentially good targets worth going after.

75
00:04:33.080 --> 00:04:35.340
It turns out that it's not just random cell lines.

76
00:04:35.400 --> 00:04:39.280
These are organized into lineages, and so there are lineages, for example,

77
00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:42.920
that have higher dependency on P300 and some that have higher dependency on

78
00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:44.720
CBP and vice versa.

79
00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:50.080
And this type of observation led us several years ago to develop a

80
00:04:50.120 --> 00:04:53.820
small molecule we call JQUAD1. This is a PROTAC that

81
00:04:54.200 --> 00:04:57.840
interacts with the cereblon E3 receptor to drive targeted

82
00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:01.180
protein degradation of P300, sparing CBP.

83
00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:05.100
And the rationale for this compound was that we wanted to target the

84
00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:05.860
dependency,

85
00:05:06.660 --> 00:05:10.460
and we knew if we were going to deliver a systemic therapy, that it might

86
00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:13.880
be best to just target one of these two proteins rather than both,

87
00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:17.580
hoping that the other one would compensate in untransformed

88
00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:21.400
tissues. And testing this in neuroblastoma cells as well as

89
00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:25.310
many others, we demonstrated that it was highly on target against P300, causing

90
00:05:25.340 --> 00:05:28.310
degradation. Along with this, we see loss of

91
00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:32.540
acetylation genome-wide. And this first-generation compound is

92
00:05:32.620 --> 00:05:36.580
well-tolerated in mice and can give you tumor growth

93
00:05:36.680 --> 00:05:37.120
slowing.

94
00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:40.300
So that there you can see some of the toxicity data.

95
00:05:41.120 --> 00:05:45.100
So this led us to the question, are there other lineages or

96
00:05:45.140 --> 00:05:48.920
other tumor types in which targeting P300 might be a nice therapeutic

97
00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:49.600
strategy?

98
00:05:50.660 --> 00:05:54.420
And so together with June Chi's lab at Dana-Farber and Brian Abraham's

99
00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:58.300
lab at St. Jude and Ben Ory's lab at the University of Nantes in France,

100
00:05:58.460 --> 00:06:02.444
we embarked on a DepMap analysisTo try to pull

101
00:06:02.484 --> 00:06:06.344
apart and look for lineages that had selective dependency on p300

102
00:06:06.444 --> 00:06:10.084
relative to CBP. And we paired that with work

103
00:06:10.604 --> 00:06:13.324
in collaboration with the Prism platform at

104
00:06:14.144 --> 00:06:17.994
the Broad Institute, testing these compounds on panels of

105
00:06:18.064 --> 00:06:21.644
bar-coded cell lines, up to about 800 cancer cell lines, to look for

106
00:06:21.704 --> 00:06:23.984
lineages that were particularly sensitive.

107
00:06:24.624 --> 00:06:27.374
And when we fused this data together, what we ended up with,

108
00:06:28.484 --> 00:06:32.414
here looking at some of the top lineages, we found that in comparison to

109
00:06:32.414 --> 00:06:36.194
neuroblastoma, which we knew this compound had nice effects in and was

110
00:06:36.224 --> 00:06:39.554
validated in, that actually osteosarcoma showed up as another

111
00:06:39.584 --> 00:06:42.044
lineage of potential interest.

112
00:06:42.964 --> 00:06:46.784
So I don't really need to introduce osteosarcoma to this audience, but just a

113
00:06:46.824 --> 00:06:50.114
few points to say this is a primary aggressive solid tumor of

114
00:06:50.224 --> 00:06:54.204
bone. We've, over the last decades, not for lack of trying,

115
00:06:54.284 --> 00:06:57.384
have made very limited advancements in drug development.

116
00:06:57.864 --> 00:07:01.774
We currently treat patients with three drugs, methotrexate, doxorubicin, and

117
00:07:01.784 --> 00:07:02.384
cisplatin.

118
00:07:03.804 --> 00:07:07.714
And here's a Kaplan-Meier curve of patients enrolled on a Phase II trials,

119
00:07:07.764 --> 00:07:10.043
and here you can see, of course, we don't do very well.

120
00:07:10.984 --> 00:07:14.664
This is a disease marked by chromothripsis and alternative lengthening of

121
00:07:14.724 --> 00:07:18.544
telomeres. It's very copy number unstable, and there are several molecular

122
00:07:18.604 --> 00:07:22.544
markers that are emerging for this disease to identify groups of

123
00:07:22.584 --> 00:07:26.324
patients who will do particularly poorly, including MYC amplification

124
00:07:26.724 --> 00:07:28.564
and loss of the tumor suppressor PTEN.

125
00:07:30.064 --> 00:07:33.824
And so we partnered with Alejandro Sweet-Cordero's

126
00:07:33.904 --> 00:07:37.344
lab at UCSF. Alejandro's lab has developed these

127
00:07:37.624 --> 00:07:41.204
low-passage, PDX-derived osteosarcoma cell lines that they've

128
00:07:41.244 --> 00:07:43.424
recently demonstrated actually are quite

129
00:07:46.144 --> 00:07:49.304
faithful in terms of recapitulating the patient's primary

130
00:07:49.364 --> 00:07:53.124
tumor. And we tested a panel of these PDX-derived cell lines

131
00:07:53.184 --> 00:07:56.924
using our small molecule and demonstrated that some of these cell lines were

132
00:07:56.964 --> 00:07:59.264
sensitive, while others were not.

133
00:07:59.304 --> 00:08:02.864
And when we looked at the genetics of those cell lines that were quite sensitive,

134
00:08:02.924 --> 00:08:06.144
what we found was that every one of the sensitive lines had a

135
00:08:06.664 --> 00:08:10.343
mutation in it that would've been predicted to hyperactivate the AKT

136
00:08:10.403 --> 00:08:14.344
pathway, either loss of PTEN or amplification of AKT, or

137
00:08:14.524 --> 00:08:17.344
activation of upstream receptor tyrosine kinases.

138
00:08:18.124 --> 00:08:21.264
And so we took some of these cell lines, we tested JQuad on them.

139
00:08:21.364 --> 00:08:25.324
You can see here we're able to deplete p300 with really very

140
00:08:25.404 --> 00:08:29.344
limited effects on CBP. Along with this, we activated apoptosis

141
00:08:29.444 --> 00:08:31.584
parked by cleaved PARP and

142
00:08:32.424 --> 00:08:36.044
lose c-MYC, a driver transcription factor in the disease.

143
00:08:36.834 --> 00:08:39.193
And so this led to two questions, the first being,

144
00:08:40.024 --> 00:08:43.744
is the degrader-driven apoptosis being driven by the loss of c-MYC?

145
00:08:43.814 --> 00:08:47.664
And then the second is, how does AKT dysregulation, is that at all

146
00:08:47.704 --> 00:08:50.164
involved in the sensitivity to this compound?

147
00:08:51.284 --> 00:08:54.584
And so to answer the first question, we took sensitive cell lines, we re-expressed

148
00:08:54.604 --> 00:08:58.464
c-MYC, and then we treated with JQuad, and what we saw was really no rescue of the

149
00:08:58.484 --> 00:09:02.264
phenotype. And so we think that the loss of MYC is actually true to an

150
00:09:02.324 --> 00:09:04.404
unrelated. JQuad is doing something else.

151
00:09:05.344 --> 00:09:09.064
And to answer the second question, we took completely insensitive cell

152
00:09:09.124 --> 00:09:13.104
lines, and we treated them to overexpress myristoylated AKT.

153
00:09:13.604 --> 00:09:17.384
We then treated with JQuad and now at high doses we're able to elicit

154
00:09:17.444 --> 00:09:18.364
some cell death.

155
00:09:19.584 --> 00:09:23.184
And so how does AKT do this? Well, AKT is an upstream

156
00:09:23.224 --> 00:09:26.954
kinase that impacts upon transcriptional regulation, and of course, p300 and

157
00:09:27.064 --> 00:09:30.444
CBP are dominant regulators of transcription, and so we looked at

158
00:09:30.524 --> 00:09:34.294
RNA-seq to start with. And so we took a panel of both sensitive and

159
00:09:34.344 --> 00:09:38.084
insensitive cell lines, as well as our engineered cells, where we

160
00:09:38.144 --> 00:09:41.504
had overexpressed myristoylated AKT and performed RNA-seq.

161
00:09:42.024 --> 00:09:45.844
And we fused this data to look for genes that were upregulated really in

162
00:09:45.884 --> 00:09:49.844
sensitive cells that were under AKT control and identified a group of

163
00:09:49.884 --> 00:09:53.784
genes. And many of these genes that are upregulated, when

164
00:09:53.824 --> 00:09:57.624
we performed ChIP-seq studies, actually now acquired new p300

165
00:09:57.664 --> 00:10:01.544
binding and new enhancer acetylation, and I'm showing you several loci

166
00:10:01.584 --> 00:10:02.904
here. These are dominant

167
00:10:04.584 --> 00:10:08.284
dependencies, genetic dependencies, that are enriched in

168
00:10:08.364 --> 00:10:12.104
AKT-dependent osteosarcomas. So for example,

169
00:10:12.204 --> 00:10:16.184
SLUG, collagen VII, and the MIBL1-BCPIP1 loci.

170
00:10:16.804 --> 00:10:20.723
And it's not just up. Genes go down as well, and those genes that go down also

171
00:10:20.764 --> 00:10:23.723
lose enhancer marking and lose p300 and CBP binding.

172
00:10:24.374 --> 00:10:28.184
And so we think AKT is driving the relocalization of p300 to

173
00:10:28.264 --> 00:10:32.104
new gene loci and in some cases, dependency loci, and that's

174
00:10:32.124 --> 00:10:33.584
really how it's playing its function.

175
00:10:35.224 --> 00:10:38.564
And so if you thought to yourself, these are AKT

176
00:10:38.624 --> 00:10:41.564
dysregulated, so why not just treat with an AKT inhibitor?

177
00:10:42.064 --> 00:10:45.494
Well, there are lots of folks, including some in the audience, who have tried this

178
00:10:45.524 --> 00:10:49.324
before, and the answer is that it slows down tumor growth, but it doesn't actually

179
00:10:49.364 --> 00:10:52.944
involute the tumor. And so we wondered what about co-targeting

180
00:10:52.964 --> 00:10:56.084
p300 and CBP? Would this show some synergy or

181
00:10:56.164 --> 00:10:59.004
additivity? And so we performed

182
00:10:59.684 --> 00:11:03.304
checkerboard synergy assays across all of our PDX lines and

183
00:11:03.344 --> 00:11:04.004
demonstrated

184
00:11:05.124 --> 00:11:08.464
some evidence of either additivity or synergy between p300

185
00:11:08.504 --> 00:11:11.564
degradation, and this tool compound,

186
00:11:11.664 --> 00:11:15.184
MK-2206, which is an AKT inhibitor

187
00:11:15.264 --> 00:11:19.094
in AKT dysregulated cell lines, but not

188
00:11:19.144 --> 00:11:22.444
in other non-AKT dysregulated lines.

189
00:11:22.464 --> 00:11:26.164
And we tested multiple other methods of inactivating p300, and it turns out that

190
00:11:26.224 --> 00:11:28.704
the best way is to use this JQuad1 degrader.

191
00:11:30.204 --> 00:11:33.624
And so is this an osteosarcoma phenomenon, or is this found across cancer?

192
00:11:33.964 --> 00:11:37.734
And so to answer that, we again went back to prism screening, this time performing

193
00:11:37.824 --> 00:11:41.764
prism synergy screens. And so in this case, you treat with a dose response of

194
00:11:41.824 --> 00:11:45.724
MK-2206, or alternatively, you treat with the exact

195
00:11:45.764 --> 00:11:49.724
same dose response, again, in 800 bar-coded cell lines, but in the

196
00:11:49.764 --> 00:11:53.624
presence of JQuad1 at an anchor dose, and we chose a low anchor dose of

197
00:11:53.664 --> 00:11:57.284
JQuad. Here what you're seeing is each individual

198
00:11:57.384 --> 00:12:01.354
line is a different cell line, and if the cell line is red, that means

199
00:12:01.364 --> 00:12:05.140
that it's dying.And so you can see here that an

200
00:12:05.220 --> 00:12:08.950
anchor dose of JQuad alone will cause death of about

201
00:12:08.980 --> 00:12:12.060
somewhere between 10% to 15% of these cells.

202
00:12:12.120 --> 00:12:15.340
And this is what a dose response of MK-2206 looks like.

203
00:12:15.360 --> 00:12:18.360
And then when you put them together, you get something that looks like this,

204
00:12:19.080 --> 00:12:20.660
suggesting additivity or synergy.

205
00:12:21.460 --> 00:12:25.220
We were worried that this was unique to MK-2206, so we used another

206
00:12:25.260 --> 00:12:28.820
AKT inhibitor called capivasertib that recently acquired FDA

207
00:12:28.860 --> 00:12:30.939
approval, and we see the exact same thing.

208
00:12:30.980 --> 00:12:34.700
In fact, if not greater effect with capivasertib.

209
00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:39.720
So how does it work? Well, first we thought there must be a genetic

210
00:12:39.760 --> 00:12:42.510
predictor or a lineage predictor. It turns out that's not true.

211
00:12:43.210 --> 00:12:46.510
And so we rank ordered cell lines by how synergistic or

212
00:12:46.580 --> 00:12:50.240
antagonistic they were. We took the top 100 and bottom 100 of

213
00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:54.180
these most synergistic, most antagonistic, extracted their full

214
00:12:54.240 --> 00:12:57.020
transcriptomes, and then did a hallmarks analysis.

215
00:12:57.700 --> 00:13:01.680
And it turns out that the most synergistic cell lines all show transcriptional

216
00:13:01.740 --> 00:13:05.430
evidence of having AKT signaling being really revved up.

217
00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:10.080
When we looked at KEGG pathways, what we saw was that downstream of this, the

218
00:13:10.120 --> 00:13:13.480
majority of KEGG pathways that were enriched were involved in ribosomal

219
00:13:13.580 --> 00:13:17.200
translation. And so actually, this made a lot of sense.

220
00:13:17.500 --> 00:13:19.779
Here you're using a targeted protein degrader,

221
00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:24.180
and cells that have really, really active

222
00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:28.040
translation, replacing the protein that you're trying to

223
00:13:28.060 --> 00:13:30.320
degrade will be somewhat insensitive.

224
00:13:31.030 --> 00:13:34.700
And so we think what's going on here is that we're using

225
00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:38.700
AKT inhibitors to actually slow down translation, and

226
00:13:38.740 --> 00:13:40.760
that's allowing JQuad to work better.

227
00:13:41.660 --> 00:13:45.500
And so to investigate that, we did some translational synthesis

228
00:13:45.620 --> 00:13:49.580
assays here in a puromycin labeling assay, and you could see that the amount of

229
00:13:49.960 --> 00:13:53.360
protein that's labeled by puromycin in this nascent

230
00:13:53.420 --> 00:13:57.220
translation assay is lower in the sensitive cell lines than it is in the

231
00:13:57.260 --> 00:14:00.730
resistant lines, suggesting that the resistant lines have a higher translational

232
00:14:00.800 --> 00:14:04.420
rate. And then we performed experiments to do

233
00:14:04.480 --> 00:14:08.310
co-treatments and showed that when you co-incubate these two drugs,

234
00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:11.580
that actually your degradation of p300 is vastly improved.

235
00:14:12.629 --> 00:14:16.580
And so lastly, just to leave you with this, we took these

236
00:14:16.620 --> 00:14:20.190
two AKT dysregulated PDXs and we performed

237
00:14:20.240 --> 00:14:23.180
orthotopic xenografts, and then we dialed back the doses of

238
00:14:23.240 --> 00:14:27.060
MK-2206 and JQuad back to about a quarter of

239
00:14:27.100 --> 00:14:29.100
what we would normally use as the MTD.

240
00:14:29.600 --> 00:14:33.320
And what we see is that, of course, these two work quite nicely together in

241
00:14:33.360 --> 00:14:36.440
terms of suppressing tumor volume, prolonging survival.

242
00:14:36.500 --> 00:14:40.040
And in some cases, we were able to do micro CT measurements of tumor

243
00:14:40.100 --> 00:14:44.040
volume. And what we saw was that, of course, the tumors were quite

244
00:14:44.100 --> 00:14:45.900
small in the combination group.

245
00:14:47.540 --> 00:14:51.420
So the key messages that AKT dysregulated osteosarcoma

246
00:14:51.480 --> 00:14:54.960
is sensitive to p300 degradation, that it is

247
00:14:55.600 --> 00:14:59.140
so because of p300 relocalization to new dependency

248
00:14:59.200 --> 00:15:02.770
loci, driving transcriptional reprogramming.

249
00:15:03.360 --> 00:15:06.490
And that these two compounds targeting AKT and

250
00:15:06.520 --> 00:15:09.990
p300 are able to

251
00:15:10.020 --> 00:15:13.880
collaborate to disrupt AKT dysregulated osteosarcoma tumor

252
00:15:13.920 --> 00:15:17.900
growth in vitro and in vivo. And finally, that we think

253
00:15:17.960 --> 00:15:20.700
that this is related to translational signatures.

254
00:15:22.420 --> 00:15:25.760
I'll just acknowledge all the folks in my lab who did the work, who are bolded.

255
00:15:26.220 --> 00:15:29.820
Our collaborators in Brian Abraham's lab, Jun Chi's lab,

256
00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:34.220
Paul Gilaher, Ben Ori, Lily Gunther, and a number of other folks

257
00:15:34.660 --> 00:15:36.060
at the Broad Institute

258
00:15:37.040 --> 00:15:40.660
at St. Jude. And then in addition, folks outside of St.

259
00:15:40.880 --> 00:15:42.560
Jude who have been very helpful along the way.

260
00:15:43.600 --> 00:15:46.940
Our funding sources and you for your attention. Thanks.

261
00:15:55.760 --> 00:15:57.599
All right. We have time for one question.

262
00:16:01.080 --> 00:16:03.500
Hi, Katie Janeway, Dana-Farber. Nice work.

263
00:16:04.560 --> 00:16:08.400
My question for you is really about the drug development future of

264
00:16:08.460 --> 00:16:09.840
something that's a p300

265
00:16:11.060 --> 00:16:12.200
inhibitor or-

266
00:16:12.440 --> 00:16:12.660
Yeah

267
00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:13.180
... degrader.

268
00:16:13.480 --> 00:16:13.880
Yeah.

269
00:16:13.890 --> 00:16:17.480
I'm thinking about toxicity and broader applicability.

270
00:16:17.840 --> 00:16:18.060
Yeah.

271
00:16:18.100 --> 00:16:18.240
Thanks.

272
00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:21.810
Yeah. So I think this is an area that is

273
00:16:22.099 --> 00:16:23.520
quite active with...

274
00:16:24.580 --> 00:16:28.440
Just walk through the poster sessions and you'll see tons of posters about this.

275
00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:32.460
I think there is the question of

276
00:16:33.380 --> 00:16:35.920
what will happen if you go after p300.

277
00:16:35.960 --> 00:16:39.610
And we've looked at a number of different normal

278
00:16:39.700 --> 00:16:41.780
developing tissues in humanized mice.

279
00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:45.980
And when you take out p300 using several different p300 degraders,

280
00:16:46.380 --> 00:16:49.720
you don't see major changes, but of course, you do see some changes.

281
00:16:49.780 --> 00:16:52.920
So I think it's going to be really challenging, and I think that it's going to be

282
00:16:53.080 --> 00:16:57.000
dependent on both the molecule that you're using and the PK

283
00:16:57.040 --> 00:16:58.400
properties of that molecule.

284
00:16:59.880 --> 00:17:03.160
So just to remind everyone, osteosarcoma happens in big people.

285
00:17:03.200 --> 00:17:06.540
They're already grown up. So perfect place to start-

286
00:17:06.700 --> 00:17:06.800
Yeah

287
00:17:07.480 --> 00:17:09.620
... if you're going into a pediatric disease. Thanks.

288
00:17:10.100 --> 00:17:12.300
If there's any drug developers in the audience, please.

289
00:17:14.881 --> 00:17:15.641
Thanks very much, guys.

290
00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:24.560
Our next speaker is Gudrun Schillenbacher.

291
00:17:27.108 --> 00:17:27.748
Did I do well?

292
00:17:29.928 --> 00:17:31.728
Thank you very much for the introduction.

293
00:17:31.768 --> 00:17:35.168
So I'll be speaking about cell-free DNA in relapsed/refractory

294
00:17:35.328 --> 00:17:38.418
neuroblastoma. These are my disclosures.

295
00:17:39.008 --> 00:17:42.608
And as a brief reminder, neuroblastoma is, of course, one of the most

296
00:17:42.648 --> 00:17:46.308
frequent cancers in young children, and we know that in high-risk

297
00:17:46.428 --> 00:17:50.328
disease, after relapse, survival remains dismal

298
00:17:50.368 --> 00:17:51.288
with only poor

299
00:17:52.248 --> 00:17:55.898
treatment options. And in the international European

300
00:17:55.988 --> 00:17:59.948
Neuroblastoma Network, SIOPEN, the BEACON trials proposed

301
00:17:59.968 --> 00:18:03.008
different treatment combinations and enrolled

302
00:18:03.588 --> 00:18:07.508
225 patients with relapsed or refractory neuroblastoma

303
00:18:07.588 --> 00:18:11.228
in 10 countries over eight years. This was a factorial

304
00:18:11.328 --> 00:18:14.928
multi-arm design, and different chemotherapy

305
00:18:15.008 --> 00:18:17.988
backbones were analyzed together, either with

306
00:18:18.108 --> 00:18:21.248
bevacizumab, resulting in a response rate of

307
00:18:21.288 --> 00:18:24.248
30%, or the anti-GD2

308
00:18:24.688 --> 00:18:28.188
dinutuximab beta, resulting in a response rate of

309
00:18:28.208 --> 00:18:31.748
35%. So we learned from this clinical

310
00:18:31.888 --> 00:18:35.728
trial that indeed some activity is observed with

311
00:18:35.788 --> 00:18:39.628
these different combinations independent of the chemotherapy

312
00:18:39.728 --> 00:18:42.688
backbones in this randomized Phase 2 setting.

313
00:18:43.188 --> 00:18:46.748
Furthermore, really distinct clinical evolution patterns in

314
00:18:46.768 --> 00:18:50.548
children with relapsed versus refractory disease were observed.

315
00:18:50.608 --> 00:18:53.928
However, to date, we don't really know the biomarkers of

316
00:18:54.048 --> 00:18:54.828
response.

317
00:18:55.648 --> 00:18:59.568
And so in the biological studies, we now want to address these

318
00:18:59.608 --> 00:19:03.128
questions and first delve into depth to the

319
00:19:03.148 --> 00:19:06.928
genomic alterations of relapsed/refractory neuroblastoma

320
00:19:07.368 --> 00:19:10.888
at the time of enrollment, but also through therapy and relapse,

321
00:19:11.328 --> 00:19:15.148
analyze their evolution, and identify mechanisms of

322
00:19:15.188 --> 00:19:17.408
tumor evolution escape and resistance.

323
00:19:18.228 --> 00:19:21.828
So we based these studies on the samples from

324
00:19:22.028 --> 00:19:25.928
192 patients enrolled in the BEACON trials, also a

325
00:19:26.628 --> 00:19:30.028
control cohort of high-risk neuroblastoma patients

326
00:19:30.168 --> 00:19:33.978
analyzed at diagnosis. For these patients, we could

327
00:19:34.028 --> 00:19:37.608
analyze either tumor samples and then sequential

328
00:19:37.728 --> 00:19:41.448
plasma samples that were collected upon enrollment and

329
00:19:41.508 --> 00:19:44.848
then every two months and at the end of treatment.

330
00:19:45.288 --> 00:19:48.608
Similar samples were collected also in the control cohort.

331
00:19:49.038 --> 00:19:52.828
And we analyzed tumor samples either, when possible, by

332
00:19:52.868 --> 00:19:56.468
tumor and germline whole exome sequencing or by an

333
00:19:56.478 --> 00:20:00.028
extended gene panel. The plasma samples then

334
00:20:00.268 --> 00:20:02.648
served for cell-free DNA extraction.

335
00:20:03.088 --> 00:20:06.988
Overall, 455 plasma samples were analyzed,

336
00:20:07.028 --> 00:20:10.648
a mean of three, one to six per patient, and these were

337
00:20:10.728 --> 00:20:14.298
analyzed by low-coverage whole genome and high-coverage

338
00:20:15.148 --> 00:20:18.068
whole exome sequencing of the cell-free DNA.

339
00:20:18.648 --> 00:20:21.908
Our bioinformatics platform aims to call

340
00:20:22.068 --> 00:20:25.848
tumor-specific versus cell-free DNA-specific

341
00:20:25.968 --> 00:20:29.728
copy number alterations and SNVs.

342
00:20:30.698 --> 00:20:34.668
And first, we want to look more in detail at the tumor-specific

343
00:20:34.708 --> 00:20:37.548
genetic alterations in this population,

344
00:20:38.088 --> 00:20:41.808
highlighting the previously known copy number alterations.

345
00:20:41.888 --> 00:20:45.608
This is no surprise, frequency of 17q gain, and

346
00:20:45.648 --> 00:20:49.238
then also the single gene alterations that we know of, MYCN

347
00:20:49.348 --> 00:20:52.988
amplification, the single gene mutations such as ALK.

348
00:20:53.528 --> 00:20:57.228
We could see that indeed upon relapse, so these are the

349
00:20:57.248 --> 00:21:01.188
relapse samples with relevant alterations and enrichment

350
00:21:01.308 --> 00:21:04.588
as previously described by us and others of ALK

351
00:21:04.668 --> 00:21:08.458
alterations as well as other alterations in the RAS/MAPK kinase

352
00:21:08.568 --> 00:21:11.708
pathways and also a more frequent occurrence of the

353
00:21:11.748 --> 00:21:15.698
recently identified FGFR1 mutations which

354
00:21:15.728 --> 00:21:19.088
confer high aggressivity in these patients.

355
00:21:19.888 --> 00:21:23.448
So following this analysis, we then wanted to look for

356
00:21:23.508 --> 00:21:27.068
prognostic factors that might be associated with outcome

357
00:21:27.508 --> 00:21:29.368
at the time of enrollment in BEACON.

358
00:21:29.848 --> 00:21:33.678
Patients with refractory disease fared better than those in

359
00:21:33.748 --> 00:21:37.568
relapse. MYCN amplification is associated with poorer

360
00:21:37.628 --> 00:21:41.608
outcome in these patients. However, the presence of ALK mutations

361
00:21:41.688 --> 00:21:45.238
or mutations in the RAS/MAPK kinase pathways were not

362
00:21:45.288 --> 00:21:48.698
associated with poorer outcome upon enrollment in BEACON.

363
00:21:49.528 --> 00:21:53.408
We then looked more in detail at analyses of cell-free DNA,

364
00:21:53.448 --> 00:21:57.408
focusing first on the overall cell-free DNA quantity

365
00:21:57.468 --> 00:22:00.968
at the time of enrollment. We can see really a very

366
00:22:01.228 --> 00:22:01.688
vast

367
00:22:02.728 --> 00:22:06.308
range of cell-free DNA concentrations from 10 to over

368
00:22:06.508 --> 00:22:08.668
1,000 nanograms per mil of plasma.

369
00:22:09.308 --> 00:22:12.868
This did not correlate with overall disease burden as

370
00:22:12.908 --> 00:22:16.748
evaluated by the SIOP and MIBG score, as you can

371
00:22:16.828 --> 00:22:20.508
see here. However, a prognostic impact of the overall

372
00:22:20.548 --> 00:22:24.478
cell-free DNA quantity at enrollment in the BEACON trials

373
00:22:24.548 --> 00:22:28.478
was observed. Those with a cell-free DNA above the cutoff fared

374
00:22:28.608 --> 00:22:28.958
worse.

375
00:22:29.788 --> 00:22:33.548
We then looked at the cell-free DNA in our sequential analyses,

376
00:22:33.888 --> 00:22:37.688
looking both at cell-free DNA quantity and the ctDNA content.

377
00:22:38.148 --> 00:22:41.708
We see that in BEACON, at the time of relapse or

378
00:22:42.448 --> 00:22:46.358
progression, lower quantities at the time of diagnosis are observed,

379
00:22:46.448 --> 00:22:50.168
and then in the follow-up samples every two months, we see,

380
00:22:50.708 --> 00:22:54.048
correlating with the response, decrease and then again

381
00:22:54.088 --> 00:22:57.708
increase at the end of treatment. And this is reflected in these

382
00:22:57.748 --> 00:23:01.428
different patient graphs where we can see these distinct

383
00:23:01.628 --> 00:23:05.608
dynamics, either of decrease and then stable persistence

384
00:23:05.648 --> 00:23:09.628
of cell-free DNA, a complete eradication, or eradication

385
00:23:09.688 --> 00:23:12.268
and then reappearance correlating with the disease

386
00:23:12.388 --> 00:23:16.024
course.Our cell-free DNA whole exome

387
00:23:16.124 --> 00:23:19.964
sequencing then enables us to call all SNVs that are

388
00:23:20.044 --> 00:23:23.884
termed tumor specific, filtered on the germline, and

389
00:23:23.904 --> 00:23:27.724
this gives us further detail on the different dynamics of the different

390
00:23:27.764 --> 00:23:31.464
mutations that we can observe with different patterns

391
00:23:31.504 --> 00:23:33.564
according to the different patients.

392
00:23:33.984 --> 00:23:37.204
Now, we wanted to analyze this more in detail, and we

393
00:23:37.264 --> 00:23:40.824
calculated the cancer cell fraction for each of the

394
00:23:41.504 --> 00:23:45.264
SNVs based not only on the variant allele fraction

395
00:23:45.604 --> 00:23:49.424
but also on purity of the sample, ploidy, and copy

396
00:23:49.504 --> 00:23:53.224
number state. And this enables us then to identify cellular

397
00:23:53.324 --> 00:23:57.004
clones, which can then, in the different models,

398
00:23:57.324 --> 00:24:00.524
identify clones determined by the different

399
00:24:01.464 --> 00:24:05.384
SNVs. And we can see as an example here, the distinct

400
00:24:06.244 --> 00:24:10.144
evolution of the different clones in a given patient with disappearance

401
00:24:10.204 --> 00:24:13.884
of one cellular clone at the follow-up sample and emergence of

402
00:24:13.984 --> 00:24:14.424
others.

403
00:24:15.244 --> 00:24:19.064
If we look more in detail at the genes targeted by these SNVs, we

404
00:24:19.103 --> 00:24:22.704
can see that those observed in cell-free

405
00:24:22.824 --> 00:24:26.544
DNA only frequently target genes which

406
00:24:26.624 --> 00:24:29.084
code for proteins important in cell-to-cell or

407
00:24:29.144 --> 00:24:31.644
cell-to-extracellular matrix

408
00:24:32.364 --> 00:24:35.854
interactions. Cell-free DNA SNVs that

409
00:24:35.884 --> 00:24:37.294
disappear upon treatment

410
00:24:38.604 --> 00:24:42.524
frequently concern molecular transducers, whereas

411
00:24:42.564 --> 00:24:46.184
those that emerge during treatment target,

412
00:24:46.304 --> 00:24:48.924
amongst others, the RAS MAP kinase pathways.

413
00:24:49.264 --> 00:24:52.684
And interestingly, we saw that frequently,

414
00:24:52.724 --> 00:24:56.324
HRAS or other RAS MAP kinase genes like to

415
00:24:56.384 --> 00:25:00.364
remain at a subclonal level, whereas other SNVs have really become

416
00:25:00.424 --> 00:25:00.874
clonal.

417
00:25:01.944 --> 00:25:05.584
Importantly, in some instances, we observed alterations in

418
00:25:05.684 --> 00:25:08.804
genes that are known to actually occur during clonal

419
00:25:08.884 --> 00:25:12.824
hematopoiesis, as in this example, a mutation in JAK3

420
00:25:13.184 --> 00:25:16.124
observed with low VAF in the cell-free DNA.

421
00:25:16.564 --> 00:25:20.364
We looked at the PBMC at the time and saw that indeed

422
00:25:20.444 --> 00:25:23.964
after treatment, this mutation was present in the cells at

423
00:25:23.984 --> 00:25:27.444
6%. Of note, this mutation was not

424
00:25:27.504 --> 00:25:31.444
identified at diagnosis for this patient, neither in the tumors nor in the

425
00:25:31.504 --> 00:25:34.654
PBMC, allowing us to conclude that this probably does

426
00:25:35.164 --> 00:25:37.664
correspond to clonal hematopoiesis.

427
00:25:38.064 --> 00:25:42.024
Further analysis is ongoing to determine the frequency of these events in our

428
00:25:42.064 --> 00:25:45.364
population. And finally, we want to study gene

429
00:25:45.444 --> 00:25:49.224
expression and infer gene expression from our cell-free

430
00:25:49.284 --> 00:25:52.724
DNA data. And in this context, it is important to

431
00:25:52.744 --> 00:25:55.944
remember that actually when cell-free DNA is

432
00:25:56.404 --> 00:25:59.824
released into the bloodstream, the actual fragment size

433
00:26:00.084 --> 00:26:03.684
depends upon the cleavage that depends upon the nucleosome

434
00:26:03.744 --> 00:26:07.564
positioning. And at transcription start sites for genes that are

435
00:26:07.584 --> 00:26:11.324
expressed, the well-defined nucleosome organization results

436
00:26:11.404 --> 00:26:15.064
then in dips upon the sequencing, whereas in less expressed

437
00:26:15.124 --> 00:26:18.184
genes, this results in a higher overall coverage.

438
00:26:18.564 --> 00:26:22.244
And we leverage this for a unique experimental design where we

439
00:26:22.264 --> 00:26:26.254
designed a capture across 34,000 transcription start sites,

440
00:26:26.344 --> 00:26:30.124
which we sequenced to a high depth across 200

441
00:26:30.184 --> 00:26:33.304
base pairs to the right and to the left of each of these.

442
00:26:33.344 --> 00:26:37.284
We then used machine learning to train our results with regards to

443
00:26:37.324 --> 00:26:41.104
coverage on the GTEx database to call expressed versus

444
00:26:41.184 --> 00:26:44.704
non-expressed genes. And then we used this on our

445
00:26:44.864 --> 00:26:45.544
targeted

446
00:26:46.564 --> 00:26:50.244
TSS regions in neuroblastoma plasma samples.

447
00:26:50.644 --> 00:26:54.364
Here are some examples when we do k-means clustering, and we can

448
00:26:54.704 --> 00:26:58.624
identify genes that are commonly predicted as

449
00:26:58.664 --> 00:27:02.484
being silent, as indicated here, AKT, or commonly

450
00:27:02.544 --> 00:27:06.044
expressed genes such as ALK and TERT in the overall

451
00:27:06.364 --> 00:27:09.604
population. We also identified genes with

452
00:27:10.704 --> 00:27:14.584
distinct expression predicted, such as this one in

453
00:27:14.624 --> 00:27:17.684
MYCN amplified versus these in MYCN

454
00:27:18.084 --> 00:27:21.664
non-amplified cases. In our context and the BEACON

455
00:27:21.764 --> 00:27:25.704
trial, we then thought it was important to look at these predicted gene

456
00:27:25.744 --> 00:27:29.684
expressions comparing the samples from diagnosis

457
00:27:29.744 --> 00:27:33.584
to relapse. And here again, in addition to the genes

458
00:27:33.684 --> 00:27:37.404
that are commonly predicted to be not expressed, so with high

459
00:27:37.524 --> 00:27:40.924
coverage or expressed with low coverage, we could identify

460
00:27:40.984 --> 00:27:44.584
clusters that were initially silent and then became

461
00:27:44.664 --> 00:27:47.984
expressed at relapse, such as STAT6 or FOXP1,

462
00:27:48.524 --> 00:27:52.444
or on the other hand, that were initially expressed and then became

463
00:27:52.584 --> 00:27:55.784
silent, such as BCORL1 and ARID5B.

464
00:27:56.624 --> 00:27:59.684
So altogether, we show in these BEACON

465
00:27:59.884 --> 00:28:03.204
biological studies an overall

466
00:28:03.584 --> 00:28:07.504
context of genetic alterations, but importantly, the

467
00:28:07.544 --> 00:28:11.244
prognostic impact of MYCN amplification in this study.

468
00:28:11.754 --> 00:28:15.544
No correlation between the cell-free DNA quantity and the SIOPEN

469
00:28:15.584 --> 00:28:19.244
score was observed, but we did see that cell-free DNA was of

470
00:28:19.264 --> 00:28:22.644
prognostic impact. The whole exome sequencing

471
00:28:22.844 --> 00:28:26.264
provides further evidence of clonal evolution, and further data

472
00:28:26.364 --> 00:28:30.304
analysis is ongoing to really identify the most frequent clones that

473
00:28:30.364 --> 00:28:33.724
emerge at the time of relapse. And we can really

474
00:28:33.764 --> 00:28:37.404
distinguish those that disappear versus those that emerge

475
00:28:37.464 --> 00:28:40.704
during treatment. We are currently finalizing

476
00:28:40.804 --> 00:28:43.464
analyses to determine the frequency of clonal

477
00:28:43.484 --> 00:28:47.384
hematopoiesis. We have a hint that that might occur

478
00:28:48.204 --> 00:28:51.904
with temozolomide treatment, which we use a lot in Europe, but that's ongoing.

479
00:28:52.404 --> 00:28:56.144
And we are working on integrating our inferred

480
00:28:56.184 --> 00:28:59.444
expression profiles with the genetic information.

481
00:29:00.053 --> 00:29:02.504
I would like to thank all collaborators.

482
00:29:02.564 --> 00:29:06.314
This work was done in my team by Yasmine Idir, Charles Bobin, Alexandre

483
00:29:06.424 --> 00:29:10.384
Saint-Chal, and I would like to thank Sally George, Lucas

484
00:29:10.424 --> 00:29:14.174
Morena, Lou Chesler, and everybody who contributed to the

485
00:29:14.264 --> 00:29:18.224
study, and importantly, patients and their families. Thank you very much.

486
00:29:27.374 --> 00:29:28.094
Thank you, Adrienne. That was

487
00:29:28.914 --> 00:29:31.253
beautiful data and very well delivered. Thank you.

488
00:29:32.374 --> 00:29:32.444
It

489
00:29:33.754 --> 00:29:37.654
was very clever with the nucleosome and differential expression, and you showed the

490
00:29:37.694 --> 00:29:40.574
extremes where not expressed and then high expressed.

491
00:29:41.474 --> 00:29:43.254
I just wonder if you've looked at things like

492
00:29:45.234 --> 00:29:48.294
mechanisms of resistance, and have you looked at the GD2 synthesis

493
00:29:48.354 --> 00:29:49.854
enzymes or-

494
00:29:49.864 --> 00:29:49.864
Yeah

495
00:29:49.864 --> 00:29:51.634
... things along those pathways?

496
00:29:51.794 --> 00:29:55.724
I must admit that this is preliminary data, and we're currently working on that.

497
00:29:55.894 --> 00:29:59.444
I had thought we'd be further along the way looking at such aspects,

498
00:29:59.514 --> 00:30:02.794
and we took a bit of delay due to a maternity leave of the

499
00:30:02.814 --> 00:30:03.944
bioinformatician, and that's-

500
00:30:03.944 --> 00:30:05.454
Congratulations, Gudrun.

501
00:30:05.514 --> 00:30:07.994
Well, not me. It's the bioinformatician.

502
00:30:08.434 --> 00:30:09.214
But hopefully

503
00:30:10.854 --> 00:30:14.214
we'll be able to pick that up, and I agree that that's a very important aspect to

504
00:30:14.254 --> 00:30:14.534
work on.

505
00:30:14.554 --> 00:30:14.634
Yeah.

506
00:30:14.654 --> 00:30:16.974
Thanks, John.

507
00:30:17.234 --> 00:30:20.454
I actually have a question about the kinetics of the cell-free DNA.

508
00:30:20.474 --> 00:30:24.334
I've always wondered, in the middle of treatment-- You said at the beginning, at

509
00:30:24.354 --> 00:30:27.624
diagnosis, it is reflective, potentially prognostic.

510
00:30:28.114 --> 00:30:31.134
But I've always wondered, in the middle of treatment, does your data demonstrate

511
00:30:31.194 --> 00:30:34.214
anything regarding the kinetics of cell-free DNA and response?

512
00:30:34.474 --> 00:30:37.974
I think that's a very important question, and what we're currently working on is

513
00:30:38.294 --> 00:30:41.654
correlating that with the clinical data. That is also ongoing.

514
00:30:41.964 --> 00:30:45.174
And so we retrieve detailed clinical data, including,

515
00:30:46.014 --> 00:30:49.914
for us in Europe, the MIBG score, to match that with the actual

516
00:30:50.414 --> 00:30:53.634
cell-free DNA data, and I think that will provide more insight.

517
00:30:53.664 --> 00:30:57.634
And I think as we move along, we'll be able to integrate that and maybe pick

518
00:30:57.694 --> 00:31:00.914
out the patients that need continuing treatment indeed.

519
00:31:01.704 --> 00:31:02.094
Thanks.

520
00:31:04.954 --> 00:31:05.374
Thank you.

521
00:31:06.214 --> 00:31:09.994
One more question. So it was interesting about the

522
00:31:10.034 --> 00:31:12.004
patterns of the clones that you were finding-

523
00:31:12.094 --> 00:31:12.174
Yeah

524
00:31:12.394 --> 00:31:16.194
... in the cell-free DNA. And so was there dominant

525
00:31:16.254 --> 00:31:18.174
patterns of clones that you were seeing across-

526
00:31:18.214 --> 00:31:18.374
Yeah

527
00:31:18.394 --> 00:31:18.624
... many, many

528
00:31:19.974 --> 00:31:21.194
children that you could--

529
00:31:21.514 --> 00:31:22.014
Yeah.

530
00:31:22.054 --> 00:31:22.064
With all the-

531
00:31:22.294 --> 00:31:26.274
So again, we frequently see clones that harbor

532
00:31:26.514 --> 00:31:29.464
RAS/MAP kinase mutations or ALK, and

533
00:31:29.514 --> 00:31:33.334
interestingly, those, even though we think they are driver genes,

534
00:31:33.643 --> 00:31:36.934
and many in this room have studied these for a long time,

535
00:31:37.314 --> 00:31:40.594
they somehow like to remain at a subclonal level

536
00:31:40.694 --> 00:31:42.804
associated with many other genes.

537
00:31:43.064 --> 00:31:45.814
So we're currently working on that, trying to figure out a model.

538
00:31:45.934 --> 00:31:49.263
I don't know why these tumors then like this

539
00:31:49.274 --> 00:31:53.054
heterogeneity. It's like an ecosystem of different cells

540
00:31:53.134 --> 00:31:56.674
that need to work together, and I think these data

541
00:31:56.794 --> 00:32:00.254
provide some insight into that and will need further modelization.

542
00:32:00.934 --> 00:32:01.554
Great. Thank you.

543
00:32:02.054 --> 00:32:03.334
Thanks.

544
00:32:08.494 --> 00:32:12.474
Our next speaker is January Zhang from Princess Margaret Cancer

545
00:32:12.554 --> 00:32:16.214
Centre in Toronto. Her talk is entitled "Spatial T Cell Receptor

546
00:32:16.294 --> 00:32:19.344
Profiling Uncovers Barriers to T Cell Engagement and Shared

547
00:32:19.414 --> 00:32:22.974
Tumor-Reactive Clonotypes in High-Risk Neuroblastoma."

548
00:32:23.834 --> 00:32:26.634
Awesome. Thanks for the introduction. Hi, everyone.

549
00:32:26.654 --> 00:32:30.114
My name is January. I'm a PhD candidate from the University of

550
00:32:30.134 --> 00:32:33.814
Toronto, and today we'll present our work with the Children's Oncology

551
00:32:33.914 --> 00:32:37.814
Group on how spatially resolved T cell receptor tracking links tumor

552
00:32:37.894 --> 00:32:41.534
immune segregation to T cell

553
00:32:41.554 --> 00:32:44.674
clonotype-specific states in high-risk neuroblastoma.

554
00:32:45.414 --> 00:32:46.733
And I have no disclosures.

555
00:32:47.914 --> 00:32:51.894
High-risk neuroblastoma, or HR-NB, is the most frequent extracranial

556
00:32:51.904 --> 00:32:55.714
solid tumor in children and typically occurs in the adrenal gland.

557
00:32:56.374 --> 00:33:00.294
Despite very intensive standard of care, including induction

558
00:33:00.374 --> 00:33:03.844
chemotherapy, consolidative stem cell transplant, and

559
00:33:03.954 --> 00:33:07.854
post-consolidation anti-GD2 therapy, the five-year survival

560
00:33:07.874 --> 00:33:11.654
rate remains at only about 50%. These limited outcomes have

561
00:33:11.694 --> 00:33:15.594
driven increasing interest in the role of the immune system, particularly

562
00:33:15.634 --> 00:33:19.234
T cells, in shaping disease progression and therapeutic

563
00:33:19.254 --> 00:33:19.734
response.

564
00:33:21.994 --> 00:33:25.814
T cells are specialized immune cells that act as one of the body's

565
00:33:25.874 --> 00:33:27.334
primary defense against cancer.

566
00:33:28.174 --> 00:33:31.894
Each T cell has a unique heterodimeric T cell receptor, or

567
00:33:31.974 --> 00:33:35.894
TCR, that allows the cell to recognize and bind to

568
00:33:35.934 --> 00:33:37.114
specific antigens.

569
00:33:38.454 --> 00:33:42.034
In neuroblastoma, conventional alpha beta T cells are detected but

570
00:33:42.074 --> 00:33:45.634
functionally constrained due to the downregulation of

571
00:33:45.674 --> 00:33:47.054
antigen-presenting molecules.

572
00:33:48.014 --> 00:33:51.974
This has therefore drawn attention to gamma delta T cells, which recognize

573
00:33:51.994 --> 00:33:54.834
their targets independent of these molecules.

574
00:33:55.894 --> 00:33:59.854
However, the actual contribution of these T cells and their TCRs

575
00:33:59.914 --> 00:34:01.634
remain largely undefined.

576
00:34:03.874 --> 00:34:07.594
So using samples from the AMBL1531 trial, we

577
00:34:07.654 --> 00:34:11.495
assembled a cohort with longitudinal sampling across 11

578
00:34:11.534 --> 00:34:13.274
clinical time points.

579
00:34:14.435 --> 00:34:17.834
So this Phase 3 clinical trial tests the efficacy of the

580
00:34:17.854 --> 00:34:21.403
radiopharmaceutical 131I-MIBG, which could

581
00:34:21.415 --> 00:34:25.054
potentially modulate antitumor immunity through enhanced

582
00:34:25.154 --> 00:34:26.374
antigen

583
00:34:27.475 --> 00:34:30.015
availability and altered T cell activation.

584
00:34:30.674 --> 00:34:34.654
In this trial, patients are randomized into either standard therapy or

585
00:34:34.814 --> 00:34:38.624
standard therapy plus I-MIBG, and currently we are still

586
00:34:38.714 --> 00:34:41.734
blinded, so we don't know which patient is assigned to which arm.

587
00:34:43.394 --> 00:34:47.234
So the cohort I want to focus on today includes paired tumor

588
00:34:47.314 --> 00:34:50.694
FFPEs from initial diagnostic biopsy and

589
00:34:50.874 --> 00:34:54.435
subsequent surgical resection from five HR-NB patients.

590
00:34:55.334 --> 00:34:59.074
Additionally, we also have matching blood samples, including

591
00:34:59.154 --> 00:35:02.354
PBMC and cell-free DNA, whenever they were available.

592
00:35:04.054 --> 00:35:07.774
So we first performed bulk TCR sequencing on our entire

593
00:35:07.814 --> 00:35:08.234
cohort,

594
00:35:09.094 --> 00:35:12.714
for TCR chains alpha, beta, gamma, and delta, which

595
00:35:12.814 --> 00:35:16.514
resulted in more than 10 million reads per sample for our tumor,

596
00:35:16.614 --> 00:35:18.154
cell-free DNA, and PBMC.

597
00:35:18.994 --> 00:35:22.794
Then from the bulk data, we selected 100 TCR

598
00:35:22.834 --> 00:35:26.638
clonotypesAnd developed custom Xenium probes

599
00:35:26.718 --> 00:35:28.038
for spatial tracking.

600
00:35:29.478 --> 00:35:33.278
And combining these with 377 additional Xenium gene

601
00:35:33.338 --> 00:35:37.038
probes for cell identity, we were able to profile the

602
00:35:37.078 --> 00:35:40.378
10 FFP tumors, allowing us to achieve in-situ

603
00:35:40.438 --> 00:35:44.258
localization of specific TCR

604
00:35:44.378 --> 00:35:48.118
clonotypes, linking specific TL states to their

605
00:35:48.178 --> 00:35:49.518
exact physical location.

606
00:35:51.058 --> 00:35:52.658
So our approach yielded

607
00:35:54.518 --> 00:35:57.978
high-resolution single-cell profiling of over two million cells.

608
00:35:58.618 --> 00:36:02.368
We found seven major cell types,

609
00:36:02.478 --> 00:36:03.868
including neural blast cells,

610
00:36:04.738 --> 00:36:06.738
macrophages, B cells, and T cells.

611
00:36:07.398 --> 00:36:11.118
And right off the bat, we observed compartmentalization across the different cell

612
00:36:11.158 --> 00:36:15.098
types, so we decided to perform a series of distance

613
00:36:15.138 --> 00:36:15.758
analyses.

614
00:36:17.238 --> 00:36:18.118
And so the first

615
00:36:21.718 --> 00:36:25.048
experiment we did was a co-occurrence analysis, which

616
00:36:25.698 --> 00:36:29.358
quantified which cell types are clustering together and which are being pushed

617
00:36:29.398 --> 00:36:33.078
apart. And across all samples, we

618
00:36:33.138 --> 00:36:37.038
observed robust self-association of the B and T cells, as

619
00:36:37.118 --> 00:36:39.738
shown by the circled red columns on the left,

620
00:36:40.658 --> 00:36:44.618
as well as on the right, where you can see T cells in black and B

621
00:36:44.678 --> 00:36:46.318
cells in maroon clustering together.

622
00:36:47.758 --> 00:36:50.738
Conversely, T and B cells are consistently depleted

623
00:36:51.658 --> 00:36:55.418
near neural blasts, as shown by the circled blue columns on the left

624
00:36:55.878 --> 00:36:59.758
and also on the right, where the yellow neural blast cells are segregated

625
00:36:59.818 --> 00:37:00.778
from the immune cells.

626
00:37:02.518 --> 00:37:06.258
Next, we asked which, if any, T cell subtypes were

627
00:37:06.318 --> 00:37:06.698
able to

628
00:37:07.538 --> 00:37:11.378
bypass the segregation. So we performed a

629
00:37:11.438 --> 00:37:15.218
neighbor analysis, which calculated the cell type

630
00:37:15.318 --> 00:37:18.298
identity for each T cell's top 10 nearest neighbors.

631
00:37:19.018 --> 00:37:22.758
And we found that gamma delta T cells have the highest proportion of

632
00:37:22.838 --> 00:37:25.758
neural blast neighbors, with neural blasts accounting for

633
00:37:25.878 --> 00:37:28.398
45% of their immediate environment.

634
00:37:29.298 --> 00:37:32.867
So this highlights gamma delta T cells as a spatially

635
00:37:32.978 --> 00:37:36.038
privileged population, capable of localized

636
00:37:36.118 --> 00:37:38.898
interactions with neural blast cells.

637
00:37:40.038 --> 00:37:43.858
Next, shifting from single-cell to tissue-level organization,

638
00:37:45.238 --> 00:37:48.858
cellular domain analysis identified distinct spatial

639
00:37:48.918 --> 00:37:52.398
domains. And again, we found that gamma delta T cells are

640
00:37:53.478 --> 00:37:57.198
highly enriched in neural blast-rich domains, as shown by the

641
00:37:57.338 --> 00:38:00.198
prominent dark blue segment in the center of this chart.

642
00:38:00.678 --> 00:38:04.578
So this demonstrates the selective recruitment or

643
00:38:04.638 --> 00:38:06.138
retention of

644
00:38:07.278 --> 00:38:09.998
gamma delta T cells to the tumor

645
00:38:10.638 --> 00:38:11.558
microenvironment.

646
00:38:12.698 --> 00:38:16.538
Finally, comparing the gene expression of T cells located

647
00:38:16.638 --> 00:38:20.338
in different domains, we found that T cells

648
00:38:21.058 --> 00:38:24.878
in neural blast-rich domains have a higher expression of the exhaustion marker

649
00:38:25.058 --> 00:38:28.558
LAG3, whereas those in immune-rich domains have a higher

650
00:38:28.618 --> 00:38:32.238
expression of CD4 and the activation marker Fos.

651
00:38:33.998 --> 00:38:37.528
Next, shifting to specific TCR clones,

652
00:38:38.018 --> 00:38:41.938
our bulk analysis identified several cross-patient TCRs that we

653
00:38:41.978 --> 00:38:44.138
prioritized for spatial tracking.

654
00:38:44.608 --> 00:38:48.458
And one prominent example is gamma clone 2,

655
00:38:48.818 --> 00:38:52.798
detected across a PBMC, cell-free DNA, and tumor of six

656
00:38:52.838 --> 00:38:56.718
patients and 10 samples across our entire cohort

657
00:38:56.758 --> 00:38:58.418
with the 11 clinical time points.

658
00:39:00.758 --> 00:39:04.708
By visualizing this clone in our primary Xenium data set, we can

659
00:39:04.798 --> 00:39:08.758
see that gamma clone 2 positive T cells, colored in maroon, are

660
00:39:08.798 --> 00:39:12.378
distributed throughout the tissue of two patients and three

661
00:39:12.498 --> 00:39:14.838
samples within our FFP cohort.

662
00:39:16.678 --> 00:39:20.318
And zooming in on the exact physical location of gamma clone 2,

663
00:39:21.118 --> 00:39:25.078
represented by blue T cells with magenta dots inside, you

664
00:39:25.118 --> 00:39:28.958
can see that this clone is frequently located adjacent to yellow

665
00:39:28.978 --> 00:39:32.728
neural blast cells. So this physical proximity,

666
00:39:32.858 --> 00:39:35.758
again, indicates that this gamma clone

667
00:39:35.918 --> 00:39:39.618
is able to infiltrate neural blast-rich

668
00:39:39.678 --> 00:39:40.217
domains.

669
00:39:42.318 --> 00:39:43.398
Finally, we assessed

670
00:39:44.358 --> 00:39:47.778
whether the phenotype of this gamma clone 2

671
00:39:47.978 --> 00:39:50.958
differs across different spatial domains.

672
00:39:51.058 --> 00:39:54.978
And we found that clone 2-positive cells located

673
00:39:55.018 --> 00:39:55.857
in immune-rich

674
00:39:56.658 --> 00:39:57.118
regions

675
00:39:58.178 --> 00:40:01.358
maintains a more progenitor-like

676
00:40:01.718 --> 00:40:05.258
phenotype with higher expression of markers like TCF7 and

677
00:40:05.358 --> 00:40:09.318
L7R, whereas those located in neural blast-rich

678
00:40:09.398 --> 00:40:13.338
domains have a more terminally exhausted phenotype with markers

679
00:40:13.358 --> 00:40:15.068
like KLRD1 and TOX.

680
00:40:16.538 --> 00:40:20.478
Finally, our platform extends beyond gamma delta T cells to conventional

681
00:40:20.538 --> 00:40:23.998
alpha beta T cells. Because the TCR is a

682
00:40:24.018 --> 00:40:27.638
heterodimer, but bulk sequencing loses chain pairing, we use a

683
00:40:27.738 --> 00:40:31.058
co-detection of both an alpha and a beta

684
00:40:31.538 --> 00:40:35.078
probe within the same cell to identify alpha beta pairs.

685
00:40:35.448 --> 00:40:39.178
And here I'm showing one example, including alpha clone

686
00:40:39.278 --> 00:40:42.808
45 and beta clone 64. And as you can see on the right,

687
00:40:43.258 --> 00:40:46.558
both of these clones have been repeatedly detected within the same cells.

688
00:40:48.958 --> 00:40:52.698
And similarly, this clone also exhibits a more terminally differentiated

689
00:40:52.738 --> 00:40:53.398
phenotype

690
00:40:54.418 --> 00:40:56.778
within neural blast-rich regions.

691
00:40:57.658 --> 00:41:01.618
We also have a few predictions for the antigen specificity of this

692
00:41:01.658 --> 00:41:04.758
clone, one of them being the cancer testis antigen

693
00:41:04.918 --> 00:41:07.138
NY-ESO-1, and that is present.

694
00:41:08.738 --> 00:41:12.318
This antigen is detected on about

695
00:41:12.438 --> 00:41:14.458
23% of all neuroblastoma tumors.

696
00:41:15.338 --> 00:41:19.138
But of course, that would require further experimental validation before we

697
00:41:19.198 --> 00:41:20.598
have a definitive answer.

698
00:41:22.078 --> 00:41:22.598
Oh, sorry.

699
00:41:23.518 --> 00:41:26.678
So in summary, our work demonstrates that tumor immune

700
00:41:26.718 --> 00:41:30.678
segregation is a defining feature of HRMB, and that gamma delta

701
00:41:30.778 --> 00:41:34.758
T cells are a spatially privileged populationThat is

702
00:41:34.778 --> 00:41:37.358
able to infiltrate immune-rich environments.

703
00:41:37.918 --> 00:41:39.658
Sorry, neuroblast-rich environments.

704
00:41:40.478 --> 00:41:43.158
And we also found that T-cell's transcriptional state is

705
00:41:44.398 --> 00:41:48.358
driven by location rather than by clonotype identity alone in

706
00:41:48.538 --> 00:41:52.138
HRMB. Going forward, we are transitioning from

707
00:41:52.218 --> 00:41:56.158
Xenium to Visium HD on fresh frozen tissue, which

708
00:41:56.178 --> 00:42:00.037
will enable the shift from targeted discovery to an

709
00:42:00.098 --> 00:42:03.778
unbiased whole transcriptome in situ localization

710
00:42:04.038 --> 00:42:05.978
of the entire TCR repertoire.

711
00:42:06.938 --> 00:42:10.718
So with that, I would like to thank the AACR for the opportunity to present this

712
00:42:10.738 --> 00:42:11.058
work,

713
00:42:11.858 --> 00:42:15.498
as well as the Department of Defense and CIHR for funding

714
00:42:15.938 --> 00:42:19.818
this project. And of course, this research would not have been possible

715
00:42:20.118 --> 00:42:23.708
without the incredible support of the Pu Lab, as well as our amazing

716
00:42:23.798 --> 00:42:24.618
collaborators.

717
00:42:25.798 --> 00:42:29.698
The manuscript for this work is currently undergoing internal review

718
00:42:29.818 --> 00:42:33.398
at the Children's Oncology Group and will soon be published as a preprint.

719
00:42:34.227 --> 00:42:37.598
And finally, I'd like to thank the audience for your attention today.

720
00:42:38.418 --> 00:42:41.818
Yeah, feel free to ask any questions now, or you can also reach out to me online.

721
00:42:42.018 --> 00:42:43.258
Thank you so much.

722
00:42:48.118 --> 00:42:51.958
Hi. Congratulations. John Anderson from University College

723
00:42:52.058 --> 00:42:52.448
London.

724
00:42:54.858 --> 00:42:56.998
You've found a really interesting clone.

725
00:42:57.698 --> 00:43:01.478
I guess you don't know what the delta pairing of that's likely to be yet, and I

726
00:43:01.518 --> 00:43:04.898
wondered if you'd identified any clonotypes yet in the

727
00:43:05.258 --> 00:43:09.018
blood samples you've also looked at and been able to correlate them to any of the

728
00:43:09.078 --> 00:43:10.578
tumor-specific clonotypes.

729
00:43:11.138 --> 00:43:12.498
Right. Thank you for your question.

730
00:43:12.878 --> 00:43:16.658
So unfortunately, we were not able to pair any gamma delta

731
00:43:16.818 --> 00:43:18.398
clones, and so

732
00:43:19.718 --> 00:43:23.338
apparently that is a very common issue in TCR work.

733
00:43:24.138 --> 00:43:27.018
I was hoping to pair them in my work, but that didn't happen.

734
00:43:28.178 --> 00:43:29.177
We did find

735
00:43:29.998 --> 00:43:32.298
quite a few interesting blood clonotypes.

736
00:43:32.878 --> 00:43:36.498
Some of them have an antigen. Some of them have a

737
00:43:36.998 --> 00:43:40.598
CDR3 sequence that is very similar to

738
00:43:41.758 --> 00:43:45.098
viral epitopes. And I also found a few

739
00:43:45.518 --> 00:43:48.978
CDR3 regions that are exclusively in neuroblastoma

740
00:43:48.987 --> 00:43:52.818
patients. Unfortunately, we found them after designing this

741
00:43:53.038 --> 00:43:56.298
Xenium panel, so we're not able to track them

742
00:43:56.378 --> 00:44:00.078
