1062
01:02:26.692 --> 01:02:28.692
So these are my disclosures.

1063
01:02:29.892 --> 01:02:33.452
We all know in the room that medulloblastoma is the most common malignant

1064
01:02:33.532 --> 01:02:37.092
pediatric brain tumor, and it's comprised of four distinct subgroups,

1065
01:02:37.492 --> 01:02:41.452
but they're uniformly all treated with maximally safe surgical resection followed

1066
01:02:41.472 --> 01:02:45.452
by chemoradiotherapy. And with this intensive regimen, we've seen an

1067
01:02:45.512 --> 01:02:48.872
increase in the five-year overall survivorship to almost 80%.

1068
01:02:49.332 --> 01:02:53.112
But our lab focuses on the most aggressive subtypes of medulloblastoma,

1069
01:02:53.552 --> 01:02:57.492
namely MYC-driven Group 3, in which the survival rates fall below 50%.

1070
01:02:58.002 --> 01:03:01.492
And these patients almost always fail to respond to standard of care and face

1071
01:03:01.512 --> 01:03:05.332
disease relapse, which is the worst complication of medulloblastoma

1072
01:03:05.392 --> 01:03:09.112
treatment. And while there exist many challenges to translating the

1073
01:03:09.152 --> 01:03:12.092
success of CAR T-cell therapies into solid tumors,

1074
01:03:12.992 --> 01:03:16.822
we really think antigen selection faces unique barriers in pediatric tumors

1075
01:03:16.832 --> 01:03:20.532
compared to their adult counterparts because of the result of somatic

1076
01:03:20.572 --> 01:03:24.532
mutations, and high mutational burden, and also

1077
01:03:24.992 --> 01:03:28.972
fewer neoantigens. And there are also challenges in finding persistent

1078
01:03:29.012 --> 01:03:32.672
or recurrent specific markers that are not lost through

1079
01:03:33.552 --> 01:03:34.832
treatment, through standard of care.

1080
01:03:35.492 --> 01:03:39.292
And as always, of course, the challenges of on-target/off-tumor talks.

1081
01:03:39.992 --> 01:03:43.552
And so to identify potential targets, we analyzed our in-house

1082
01:03:43.672 --> 01:03:47.172
proteomics data set of chemotherapy-resistant metastatic

1083
01:03:47.272 --> 01:03:51.181
MYC-driven Group 3 medulloblastoma cell lines, and we prioritized the

1084
01:03:51.212 --> 01:03:55.092
top 25% most abundant proteins from over 9,000 total

1085
01:03:55.112 --> 01:03:58.252
proteins by their differential expression between normal

1086
01:03:58.992 --> 01:04:01.612
cells and medulloblastoma cell expression.

1087
01:04:01.642 --> 01:04:05.092
And when we subsequently screened for proteins that were transmembrane,

1088
01:04:05.632 --> 01:04:09.332
we identified these nuclear envelope proteins as our top candidates.

1089
01:04:09.832 --> 01:04:13.392
And of course, these would not have been detected by a canonical CAR T-cell target

1090
01:04:13.412 --> 01:04:14.412
discovery pipeline.

1091
01:04:15.612 --> 01:04:19.392
So profiling our MYC-driven Group 3 medulloblastoma cell lines identified very

1092
01:04:19.652 --> 01:04:23.592
abundant LBR and TMPO expression across Group 3

1093
01:04:23.632 --> 01:04:27.532
medulloblastoma, with more ubiquitous expression of TMPO across normal

1094
01:04:27.592 --> 01:04:31.502
in Group 4 medullo. And notably, LBR expression was closely

1095
01:04:31.572 --> 01:04:34.972
linked to c-MYC expression and elevated specifically in our

1096
01:04:35.012 --> 01:04:38.752
MYC-amplified Group 3 medulloblastoma compared to normal neural

1097
01:04:38.772 --> 01:04:42.372
stem cells, normal human astrocytes, and indeed, all of the other

1098
01:04:42.412 --> 01:04:43.932
medulloblastoma subgroups.

1099
01:04:45.632 --> 01:04:49.052
So we went on to do some really beautiful high-resolution

1100
01:04:49.112 --> 01:04:53.052
microscopy with our colleagues, Jorge and Giedre Kair ensiuite

1101
01:04:53.172 --> 01:04:56.212
at St. Jude Children's Hospital. And

1102
01:04:57.012 --> 01:05:00.392
you can see here that there's really LBR and TMPO

1103
01:05:00.552 --> 01:05:04.452
co-localization to the nuclear envelope, to the endoplasmic

1104
01:05:04.512 --> 01:05:08.472
reticulum, and also to the plasma membrane, again, really only in the Group

1105
01:05:08.552 --> 01:05:12.492
3 medulloblastoma cells. And flow cytometry also shows that

1106
01:05:12.552 --> 01:05:15.872
only LBR and TMPO co-localize with the plasma membrane.

1107
01:05:16.352 --> 01:05:20.052
In the neural stem cells, these nuclear

1108
01:05:20.092 --> 01:05:23.612
envelope proteins did not significantly correlate to the plasma membrane

1109
01:05:23.652 --> 01:05:26.852
markers. And really, we thought this highlights an

1110
01:05:26.932 --> 01:05:30.562
untapped therapeutic opportunity where

1111
01:05:30.872 --> 01:05:34.852
this is tucked inside normal cells safely, but it's overexpressed and on the

1112
01:05:34.892 --> 01:05:36.812
surface of Group 3 medulloblastoma.

1113
01:05:38.272 --> 01:05:40.632
And so we did some orthogonal validation of these

1114
01:05:41.592 --> 01:05:45.172
proteins with TIRF microscopy imaging, which showed the same

1115
01:05:45.212 --> 01:05:47.852
results that I've described to you on the previous

1116
01:05:47.872 --> 01:05:51.816
slide.And then to truly validate our cell surface

1117
01:05:51.876 --> 01:05:55.436
finding and with help from the Jason Moffatt Lab at SickKids, we generated MYC

1118
01:05:55.576 --> 01:05:59.516
group 3 medulloblastoma cell lines that were endogenously tagged with either halo

1119
01:05:59.536 --> 01:06:03.006
or mNeon tags through CRISPR-Cas9 genome editing

1120
01:06:03.496 --> 01:06:06.986
such that all the LBR proteins expressed in our patient-derived lines were tagged

1121
01:06:07.016 --> 01:06:10.996
at the N-termini. And then we used an impermeable cell dye such that only

1122
01:06:11.016 --> 01:06:14.776
cell surface-exposed LBR will produce a true plasma membrane-associated

1123
01:06:14.896 --> 01:06:15.295
signal.

1124
01:06:17.876 --> 01:06:21.616
So now that we've... And we actually went to also look through

1125
01:06:21.676 --> 01:06:25.296
this beautiful proteomic data set from our colleagues in the Poul Sorensen lab,

1126
01:06:25.756 --> 01:06:29.396
and you can see that LBR is also a prognostic marker for medulloblastoma

1127
01:06:29.476 --> 01:06:33.456
patients, and importantly, it's significantly enriched at recurrence

1128
01:06:33.496 --> 01:06:34.536
or post-therapy.

1129
01:06:35.656 --> 01:06:38.616
And in fact, when we put mice through our

1130
01:06:39.316 --> 01:06:43.036
therapy-adapted models in the lab, you can see that these patient-derived

1131
01:06:43.056 --> 01:06:44.816
xenograft mice treated with

1132
01:06:45.896 --> 01:06:49.496
the ACNS 0935 therapy protocol

1133
01:06:49.956 --> 01:06:53.886
actually enrich the expression of LBR through therapy.

1134
01:06:56.656 --> 01:06:59.956
So now that we've thoroughly validated the exclusive presentation of these nuclear

1135
01:06:59.996 --> 01:07:03.946
envelope proteins on the surface of group 3 medulloblastoma cells and not on normal

1136
01:07:03.976 --> 01:07:07.946
cells, we can now convince our antibody engineers that a therapeutic approach is

1137
01:07:07.976 --> 01:07:11.786
warranted. And so this led to a campaign for the rational development of

1138
01:07:11.916 --> 01:07:15.706
second-generation CAR T cells targeting LBR and TMPO for the

1139
01:07:15.776 --> 01:07:18.256
treatment of MYC-driven group 3 medulloblastoma.

1140
01:07:18.706 --> 01:07:22.276
And our wonderful antibody engineers, Kevin Henry and Martin Risotti from

1141
01:07:22.336 --> 01:07:25.696
NRC, started with the generation of some in-house camelid

1142
01:07:25.776 --> 01:07:27.156
single-domain antibodies.

1143
01:07:29.676 --> 01:07:32.596
And here you can see we carried out an extensive campaign to pick the most

1144
01:07:32.636 --> 01:07:35.896
sensitive and specific clones before cloning the best binders into our

1145
01:07:35.936 --> 01:07:38.076
second-generation CAR T-cell backbone.

1146
01:07:38.516 --> 01:07:42.476
And in all of the cases, we found that the single domain antibodies against LBR,

1147
01:07:42.606 --> 01:07:46.236
the SCFVs against LBR, and the single domain antibodies against

1148
01:07:46.276 --> 01:07:50.156
TMPO, all cloned into CAR T cells, showed efficacy

1149
01:07:50.176 --> 01:07:54.096
at 4:1 E:T ratios, and they cleared tumors both in

1150
01:07:54.136 --> 01:07:56.296
vitro and in vivo, which I'll expand on

1151
01:07:56.336 --> 01:07:59.856
later. Meanwhile, back at the lab,

1152
01:08:00.395 --> 01:08:04.146
our MD-PhD student, Yujin Suk, who is the

1153
01:08:04.216 --> 01:08:05.816
primary author on all of this work...

1154
01:08:06.176 --> 01:08:09.296
And I forgot to mention at the beginning that this work is unpublished, so please

1155
01:08:09.336 --> 01:08:09.936
don't post.

1156
01:08:11.136 --> 01:08:14.976
Yujin basically wanted to examine the proliferative capacity of LBR positive

1157
01:08:15.036 --> 01:08:17.797
and LBR negative sorted medulloblastoma cells.

1158
01:08:18.576 --> 01:08:22.416
And you can see here that she found that the LBR positive cells are highly, highly

1159
01:08:22.456 --> 01:08:26.376
enriched in all of the cell cycle pathways when we did RNA

1160
01:08:26.436 --> 01:08:30.276
sequencing on those cells. And here you can see that the LBR

1161
01:08:30.656 --> 01:08:34.476
negative cells remain in G1 when we did cell cycle analysis, but the LBR

1162
01:08:34.516 --> 01:08:37.726
positive cells are the continually very, very highly cycling

1163
01:08:37.797 --> 01:08:41.276
populations. And I'll remind everyone, of course, that when you send a quick

1164
01:08:41.337 --> 01:08:45.196
section for medulloblastoma from the OR, the pathologist will report

1165
01:08:45.236 --> 01:08:47.496
back how highly proliferated it is.

1166
01:08:47.536 --> 01:08:51.396
And obviously, sometimes we see Ki-67s very alarmingly of up to

1167
01:08:51.436 --> 01:08:53.217
97% or 98%.

1168
01:08:54.677 --> 01:08:58.566
Back at the University of Toronto, Karim Mikhael had published this beautiful

1169
01:08:58.596 --> 01:09:02.556
paper on DNA double-strand break capturing nuclear envelope

1170
01:09:02.677 --> 01:09:03.316
tubules,

1171
01:09:04.156 --> 01:09:06.217
more colloquially known as DSB NETs.

1172
01:09:06.717 --> 01:09:10.596
And these DSB NETs seem to drive DNA repair, and this piqued our interest

1173
01:09:10.637 --> 01:09:13.666
because he had studied everything in triple-negative breast cancer lines

1174
01:09:14.677 --> 01:09:18.416
which aren't nearly as proliferative as the medulloblastoma cells I just mentioned.

1175
01:09:18.976 --> 01:09:22.405
So we know that DNA double-strand breaks can move to the nuclear periphery for

1176
01:09:22.596 --> 01:09:26.337
repair, and human nuclear envelope localizes to the double-strand

1177
01:09:26.356 --> 01:09:30.316
breaks in a manner depending on DNA damage response kinases and cytoplasmic

1178
01:09:30.396 --> 01:09:34.356
microtubules. So in this paper, Mikhael showed that the factors

1179
01:09:34.436 --> 01:09:38.156
collaborate with link proteins, nuclear pore complex proteins,

1180
01:09:38.465 --> 01:09:42.056
nuclear lamina, and kinesin engines, and with

1181
01:09:42.156 --> 01:09:45.286
LBR to generate these DSB capturing

1182
01:09:46.076 --> 01:09:49.816
nuclear envelope tubules or DSB NETs, which seem to be critical factors in

1183
01:09:49.856 --> 01:09:51.465
genome organization and stability.

1184
01:09:51.936 --> 01:09:55.616
So considering the very high DNA damage level and nuclear deformations in

1185
01:09:55.736 --> 01:09:59.696
cancer, as shown here when we stained our lines with P53

1186
01:09:59.716 --> 01:10:03.656
and other DDR proteins, we hypothesized that DSB NETs could mediate

1187
01:10:03.696 --> 01:10:07.676
the repair of accumulating DNA damage and optimize repair protein

1188
01:10:07.736 --> 01:10:10.336
engagement and promote non-homologous end joining.

1189
01:10:10.916 --> 01:10:12.956
So we turned to Dr. Ray Truant and Dr.

1190
01:10:13.036 --> 01:10:16.856
Carlos Baba at the COM Imaging Facility at McMaster University, who

1191
01:10:16.976 --> 01:10:18.716
used super-resolution microscopy

1192
01:10:19.536 --> 01:10:21.796
in order to stain our cells for LBR in green.

1193
01:10:22.056 --> 01:10:25.196
You can see lamin B in magenta, and the DNA is in blue.

1194
01:10:26.676 --> 01:10:30.456
And what we see here is that there's severe membrane invaginations, which we think

1195
01:10:30.576 --> 01:10:34.276
really resembled the Mikhael paper's photos of DSB NETs.

1196
01:10:34.696 --> 01:10:38.536
And there's microtubular retraction causing fracturing of the nuclear membrane.

1197
01:10:38.546 --> 01:10:42.036
So fragments of the nuclear membrane bearing LBR can be thrown up to the plasma

1198
01:10:42.096 --> 01:10:46.036
membrane, where there seems to be an inside-out fusion that happens.

1199
01:10:46.076 --> 01:10:50.006
The double-strand break repair is high, so the DSB NET activity is

1200
01:10:50.016 --> 01:10:53.536
high, and there's a great chance of nuclear envelope damage upon

1201
01:10:53.556 --> 01:10:57.336
microtubular retraction, which nets membrane fragments that end up on the plasma

1202
01:10:57.396 --> 01:11:01.316
membrane, fusing inside out. And the LBR pulls apart from the

1203
01:11:01.356 --> 01:11:05.276
nucleus from prophase to anaphase when the nuclear envelope breaks down, and in

1204
01:11:05.336 --> 01:11:08.806
telophase, the nuclear envelope membrane is very stressed and

1205
01:11:08.876 --> 01:11:12.076
fractured. So here you can see the LBR at the cell

1206
01:11:12.116 --> 01:11:16.006
membrane and in the cytoplasm, and it's marked here in purple in

1207
01:11:16.036 --> 01:11:18.926
these beautiful images. So the 3D images are striking.

1208
01:11:19.356 --> 01:11:23.325
LBRs are at the cell surface, and those invaginations go right

1209
01:11:23.336 --> 01:11:26.876
through the nucleus. And you can really see this invagination

1210
01:11:27.556 --> 01:11:31.356
pattern shows a structurally stressed nucleus because of double-strand

1211
01:11:31.396 --> 01:11:33.976
breaks matched with higher rates of mitosis.

1212
01:11:34.036 --> 01:11:37.940
This gives a better chance of membrane fragmentation.So back to the

1213
01:11:37.980 --> 01:11:40.900
targeting strategy now. We think we may have

1214
01:11:40.980 --> 01:11:44.970
uncovered a mechanism by which LBR is aberrantly mislocalized to

1215
